Core idea

You want to test monotonicity, not magnitude.

So you visualize:

Expected carry â†’ as a rank or standardized score

Realized excess return â†’ normalized by horizon volatility or carry scale

This answers:

Is higher expected carry â†’ higher realized outcome?

Without relying on portfolio sizing, leverage, or scale?

1ï¸âƒ£ Primary plot: Quantile monotonicity plot (gold standard)
What to plot

X-axis: Expected carry rank (e.g. deciles or ventiles)

Y-axis: Mean realized excess return (or t-stat) over horizon

Each point is:

â€œBonds in carry quantile q â†’ average realized outcomeâ€

Why this is invariant

Ranks eliminate scale

No portfolio weights

No leverage

No distributional assumptions

Interpretation

Upward sloping â†’ carry has alpha content

Flat â†’ no signal

Non-monotone / hump-shaped â†’ selection bias or execution effects

Downward â†’ carry is misleading (reject)

Reviewer-safe framing

â€œWe evaluate whether ex-ante carry induces a monotone ordering of realized outcomes.â€

